hints_latex:
We have a differential equation to model the \textbf{rate} of the amount
of money. What techniques do we have to turn that rate,

\begin{align*}
\frac{\textrm{d}y}{\textrm{d}t}
\end{align*} into the actual amount of money left
owed, $y(t)$?

sols_latex:
From
{part
(a)}, we have

\begin{align*}
\frac{dy}{dt} = 0.05y - A,
\end{align*}

which we will solve by separation of variables. Knowing the solution
will allow us to give a condition on $A$ so that after 25 years, the
balance owed is zero.

We notice that the equation is separable and rearrange to find

\begin{align*}
\frac{dy}{0.05y - A} = dt.
\end{align*}

Now we integrate to get

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{dy}{0.05y - A} = 20 \ln |0.05 y - A| = t + C.
\end{align*}

Therefore,

\begin{align*}
\ln|0.05y - A| &= t/20 + C/20\\
|0.05y - A| &= e^{t/20+C/20} = e^{C/20}e^{t/20}\\
0.05y - A &= F e^{t/20}
\end{align*}

where $F$ is an arbitrary constant that comes out of the integration,

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
\pm e^{C/20}
\end{align*}

in this case.

After one last rearrangement, we see that the amount of money owed after
$t$ years is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}y(t) = 20A + 20Fe^{t/20}
\end{align*}

or

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}y(t) = 20A + Ge^{20t}
\end{align*}

for another arbitary constant $G$.

From the initial condition, $y(0) = 240 000$ so $20A + G = 240 000$ or
$G = 240,000-20A$. Finally then our full equation for the amount of
money owing, $y(t)$ is,

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}y(t) = (240000-20A)e^{t/20} + 20A.
\end{align*}

Setting $y(25) = 0$ (which corresponds to having no money owing after 25
years) forces

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}(240000-20A)e^{25/20} + 20A = 0
\end{align*}

so

\begin{align*}
A = \frac{240000e^{25/20}}{20(e^{25/20}-1)} = \frac{12000e^{5/4}}{e^{5/4}-1}=16818.61.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the annual payments are $A$ = \textbackslash{}\$16818.61.

From
{part
(a)} we have that

\begin{align*}
\frac{\textrm{d}y}{\textrm{d}t}=0.05y(t)-A
\end{align*}

with the initial amount of money owed being $y(0)=240 000$. The goal is
to solve this equation for the rate of $y$ so that we can actually
obtain the quantity we want, $y(t)$ which is the money owed after $t$
years. Consider the substitution,

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}u(t)=0.05y-A
\end{align*}

which implies that

\begin{align*}
\frac{\textrm{d}u}{\textrm{d}t}=0.05\frac{\textrm{d}y}{\textrm{d}t}.
\end{align*}

Therefore we can rewrite (and simplify) our differential equation as

\begin{align*}
\frac{\textrm{d}u}{\textrm{d}t}=ru
\end{align*}

which we recognize as the exponential model and so we know the solution
is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}u(t)=B\exp(0.05t)
\end{align*}

with $B$ an arbitrary constant. This solution can also be determined
from separation of variables and integration. Putting back into our
original variable, $y(t)$, we get

\begin{align*}
y(t)=\frac{B\exp(0.05t)+A}{0.05}.
\end{align*}

which is our desired equation for the amount owed on the mortgage after
time $t$. Using the initial condition

\begin{align*}
y(0)=\frac{B+A}{0.05}=240 000
\end{align*}

we get that $B=12000-A$. Therefore we are able to write the amount of
money owed solely in terms of the annual payments, $A$,

\begin{align*}
y(t)=\frac{(12000-A)\exp(0.05t)+A}{0.05}.
\end{align*}

Now when $t=25$, we want that the mortgage is paid off, i.e., we want
the amount of money we owe to be zero. Therefore we seek that $y(25)=0$.
Therefore,

\begin{align*}
0&=\frac{(12000-A)\exp(0.05 \cdot 25)}{0.05}\\
A&=\frac{12000\exp(0.05 \cdot 25)}{\exp(0.05 \cdot 25)-1}=16818.61.
\end{align*}

Therefore, in order to pay off the mortgage in 25 years, we require that
$A$ = 16818.61. Recall that when we started paying the mortgage at year
zero we owed 80\% of the value or 240 000 dollars. If we want to find
out how much we really paid, we just need to multiply our annual rate,
$A$ by 25 years to get \textbackslash{}\$420 465.25. Add this to the
\textbackslash{}\$60 000 we already paid up front then our
\textbackslash{}\$300 000 dollar house has actually cost us
\textbackslash{}\$480 465.25!
